title: Grateful Dead Live at Palais Des Sports on 1974-09-21
description: Bertha, Mexicali Blues, Sugaree, Promised Land, Peggy-O, Me & My Uncle, Eyes Of The World-> China Doll Phil & Ned-> Playin' In The Band Playin' In The Band, Row Jimmy, Big River, Ship of Fools, Uncle John's Band, Around & Around, Morning Dew, Sugar Magnolia, E: Casey Jones

reviews.review_text: Another '74 gem I'm surprised I'm first to write on this but kudos to Charlie Miller for another great transfer and posting. One reel generation gives a minimal background hiss which is perfectly acceptable: It wouldn't bother me on a Dick's Picks and it doesn't disturb me here. Nice stereo seperation of the instruments and sonic imaging. The playing is laid back and languid in a joyous Dead kinda way. Peggy O slides along like a row boat ride on a slow moving water. Love the Eyes intro. with Billy K. Enjoy this kiddies, it's another '74 gem.

Under-rated show This is a killer show. Phil is smokin throughout. The set list is missing (after Me & my Uncle) Deal, The Race is On, a funky Loose Lucy and El Paso. Phil is just trickin during Eyes and the bass in Morning Dew is unreal. My opinion is best Dew I've heard as far as Phil goes. The bombs are astounding. The whole show really is a testement to what makes Phil different than all the rest. Can anyone say "lead" bass. To bad this show had to happen in France. 5 stars all around. The energy, the sound, the set list and a great mix. I guess its pretty easy to tell I like this show. Just listen and Smile, Smile, Smile!
interesting Deal the band sounds loose and funky - check out the extended intro to deal!

well worth the listen The "sound" of this show typifies '74---ever notice how each year has a fairly distinctive "sound"?   Most of us can listen to any show without knowing the exact year & pin it down.   
Anyway, this is worth listening to regardless of what your favorite year is.   Everyone is clearly heard---especially Phil.   Morning Dew seemed to have a kinda shaky start, but turned into a head blaster.   I LOVE the last third of the song where Jerry comes in so quiet and builds up to the explosion that Moring Dew can sometimes end with.
5 STARS for sound & the show.   And remmeber, it's ALL in how the music makes YOU FEEL!!!

Amazing bass And fine playing by the whole band throughout the show, even if less maenadic than they could sometimes be at their familiar US venues.

The Seastones is special: it begins like other performances with Phil and Ned, but after a while they pass the baton to Jerry, Keith and Bill who continue the calm spacey improvisation.
Pride of Paris Sit back and enjoy this laid back crisp show.  Sound quality is great, every instument and vocal clear.  A Phil Lovers Delite!
Killer Phil Phil is grooving like a mudder-farker on this recording.  Can't see a reason not to give it 5.

Bobby's rhythm guitar almost completely absent.  Bummer.  You can pick it out at at start of Row Jimmy, but it's soon buried in the mix like so many Healy shows. Pity... :-(  
SBD mix - 2**
Overall - 3***

SBD tapes were usually sound reinforcement mixes. The thing you need to understand is that, unless they were recording for a live album, the sbd mix wasn't meant to be used for later listening - it was used to reinforce the sound of the PA and properly mix the sound in the hall for the audience. 

Therefore if Weir was louder on stage he would be quieter on the sbd feed and vice versa. 

Unless a mix specifically meant for later listening was created then most sbd tapes will be far from perfect recordings. That's why the Betty boards sound so good - she was using a seperate mix she made just for recording.

not bad this performance is miles ahead of the previous night. i particularly like the Eyes Of The World - there are some beautiful, unique, and jazzy passages in this one. Not the best of the year by any means, but a very satisfying version, if you can dig a more mellow, Garcia driven performance.  

There are some other nice cuts too, like Deal, however, i wouldn't call any show from this tour (9/18 being the exception) great exactly. Morning Dew is a train-wreck. 

stick with winterland 2/22-24 and May-August for the best of '74...

Excellent sound quality but the mix is off... Another somewhat lackluster performance is saved by a few rather compelling passages. An unspectacular first set climaxes with a well played but dark and edgey 17 minute performance of Eyes of the World that features a thrashing Garcia solo and some sinister Lesh ordinance, prior to an eerie segue into China Doll. Not that it's my thing, but the Phil and Ned segment, with participation from Garcia, just might be the best ever Seastones ever performed. The following Playin' in the Band (with Lagin sitting in), is one of the highlights of the tour (in spite of some horrendous vocals by Donna). It's an epic performance of the song, that includes two drum breaks. Ned Lagin sits in for the remainder of the performance that features a 17 minute performance of Morning Dew. Several reviewers that I respect have given this show rather strong reviews. In deference to them I'll give this a score of 91 pts, but I'm thinking this is too generous. (91 pts)
